So give us some of the laws.

00:09:21.880 --> 00:09:23.480
We coordinated a little bit beforehand

00:09:23.700 --> 00:09:25.640
and there's some interesting laws

00:09:25.840 --> 00:09:27.320
for designing good APIs.

00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:31.100
Like one of them is the reverse Conway maneuver,

00:09:31.260 --> 00:09:34.340
which to me sounds like a jujitsu sort of move

00:09:34.760 --> 00:09:35.700
that you might try to pull.

00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:36.300
What is this?

00:09:38.020 --> 00:09:38.460
Oh, yes.

00:09:38.960 --> 00:09:48.040
So when you are designing any system, you got to think about the way it's going to end up and the laws that are going to govern them.

00:09:48.460 --> 00:09:51.480
And Conway's law is one of the main laws that do that.

00:09:52.260 --> 00:09:59.760
To explain that to people in simple terms, if you have four teams designing a compiler, you're going to have a four pass compiler.

00:10:00.660 --> 00:10:12.160
And essentially, the way you set up communications within your company, the way you set up your teams, your structure is going to be reflected in your product and you can't do anything about it.

00:10:12.270 --> 00:10:19.680
You can spend money, you can coordinate people, but at some point, Conway's Law is going to affect you and it's going to be harsh.

00:10:20.840 --> 00:10:28.240
So one of the ways to, I guess, go around it is to first think of an interface that you want to provide.

00:10:28.640 --> 00:10:30.660
And it applies to anything, not just APIs.

00:10:31.200 --> 00:10:32.980
API is just a really good example of that.

00:10:33.560 --> 00:10:43.700
And then design your company and the communications within your company, the teams within your company, to reflect the interfaces that you want to get in the end.

00:10:44.320 --> 00:10:45.700
And that's reverse con with Mo.

00:10:45.880 --> 00:10:46.080
Okay.

00:10:46.430 --> 00:10:50.660
Because your code and your APIs and all those things are going to reflect your company structure.

00:10:50.760 --> 00:10:56.200
and culture. So instead of having that being implicit, make it more explicit by saying,

00:10:57.120 --> 00:11:02.460
well, this is the end point that we want, the end result that we want. How do we work that

00:11:02.680 --> 00:11:09.540
backwards to end up structuring teams or whatever to get this, right? Precisely, yes. Yeah, it is a

00:11:09.540 --> 00:11:17.479
little bit like Jiu-Jitsu. But there are more laws that do that. Of course, there is REST, which I

00:11:17.500 --> 00:11:25.260
guess not really lost principles um which uh most people or at least most companies i saw

00:11:25.980 --> 00:11:31.520
don't really like to follow it to the letter uh but if you do uh making you know

00:11:33.270 --> 00:11:40.880
if you do follow rest if you try to make your api as available as as you can and as standardized as

00:11:40.880 --> 00:11:45.399
you can then it's much easier for new people especially junior developers to learn and then

00:11:45.400 --> 00:11:49.360
And that makes it much easier for your clients to integrate with you, which is great.

00:11:51.820 --> 00:11:55.600
There are also a few, I guess, more advanced things.

00:11:55.640 --> 00:11:59.240
For example, when you are designing an API, when you're doing microservices,

00:11:59.440 --> 00:12:01.520
and when you have many services talking to each other,

00:12:03.300 --> 00:12:08.600
which in the end provide your final product to your customers,

00:12:09.620 --> 00:12:14.820
a good idea is to omit any internal APIs and make all of your APIs,

00:12:15.040 --> 00:12:17.680
or at least the majority of your API is external.

00:12:17.910 --> 00:12:20.600
That is also one of the things about API First.

00:12:21.100 --> 00:12:23.260
Once all of your APIs are external,

00:12:23.350 --> 00:12:27.560
it means that your clients will be able to build a product

00:12:27.860 --> 00:12:29.640
that is of similar quality to yours.

00:12:30.460 --> 00:12:32.520
We're using your APIs, using your data,

00:12:33.160 --> 00:12:36.360
which provides them with infinite capabilities of using you,

00:12:36.430 --> 00:12:37.140
which is great.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:38.780
Yeah, that is great.

00:12:39.980 --> 00:12:42.220
It's certainly frustrating when you see,

