00:14:03.040 --> 00:14:04.820
We know what versioning is in Python.

00:14:05.740 --> 00:14:08.180
We have lock files.

00:14:08.860 --> 00:14:09.900
We pin the version.

00:14:10.120 --> 00:14:15.840
We might say we're using Pydantic 2.0.5 or whatever it is.

00:14:16.520 --> 00:14:20.580
And that leaves the Pydantic team free to do whatever they want.

00:14:20.860 --> 00:14:24.080
And we can trust that our code is going to stay the way it stayed.

00:14:25.380 --> 00:14:30.300
I guess API versioning is that, but for web endpoints rather than software.

00:14:32.080 --> 00:14:38.120
Yeah, and it's a little different, though, in some regards.

00:14:38.380 --> 00:14:48.900
For example, when you're packaging your, I don't know, software and you just send it to clients, the thing is you need to have versions for every single thing.

00:14:49.020 --> 00:14:55.380
For example, if we are doing a bug fix and we need to ship that to our clients, that is going to be a separate version.

00:14:56.080 --> 00:15:03.100
But in web, when you're hosting it on a server and your clients just make requests to your servers, you don't need that.

00:15:03.420 --> 00:15:06.460
You don't need to ship bug fixes as separate versions.

00:15:06.620 --> 00:15:11.900
You can just ship them because they're not going to break anything for your clients and your clients will be able to automatically get them.

00:15:12.460 --> 00:15:13.840
Same goes for minor versions.

00:15:14.840 --> 00:15:19.600
Minor versions that just add features don't really need to be a version on APIs.

00:15:20.100 --> 00:15:34.920
That leaves us with just major versions, which is why many companies like Stripe at Monite use dates for their versions because we don't really need all of the power of semantic versioning.

00:15:36.060 --> 00:15:40.260
Yeah, sure. More calendar versioning because all you really need to say is,

00:15:40.420 --> 00:15:41.580
this one is different than before.

