He has supported API versioning at Stripe for a while

00:31:01.780 --> 00:31:07.760
and he has helped us with building our API versioning approach.

00:31:08.800 --> 00:31:11.060
Essentially, what Stripe did is said,

00:31:11.100 --> 00:31:14.880
okay, let's imagine that our developers are only supporting one version,

00:31:14.960 --> 00:31:17.900
the latest one, just like with serializers.

00:31:18.480 --> 00:31:21.320
But instead of serializing every version to the latest one,

00:31:22.040 --> 00:31:26.640
let's say that each version knows how to serialize into the next version.

00:31:28.020 --> 00:31:28.720
So let's say that...

00:31:28.720 --> 00:31:29.840
Kind of like database migrations.

00:31:31.300 --> 00:31:31.460
Exactly.

00:31:32.180 --> 00:31:36.140
So let's say that I return response from the latest version.

00:31:37.210 --> 00:31:42.940
This response, or at least they call them, I think, version gates.

00:31:43.920 --> 00:31:46.760
These version gates, the version gate for fifth version,

00:31:47.320 --> 00:31:50.600
knows how to convert back my response back into the fourth version.

00:31:51.300 --> 00:31:55.480
The version gate for the fourth version knows how to convert it back into the third version.

00:31:56.240 --> 00:32:00.660
And all of a sudden, you get simple version gates.

00:32:00.720 --> 00:32:03.600
because if it's just field renaming in a single version,

00:32:03.690 --> 00:32:04.700
then it's just a single line.

00:32:04.950 --> 00:32:05.760
They're really simple.

00:32:07.420 --> 00:32:09.140
But at the same time, they're immutable

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:11.240
because these version gates,

00:32:11.460 --> 00:32:12.940
they're not describing the whole schema.

00:32:13.230 --> 00:32:15.980
They're describing the difference between two versions.

00:32:16.470 --> 00:32:19.920
And because we know that we don't want to change the old version,

00:32:20.940 --> 00:32:23.240
we want the old version to work,

00:32:23.530 --> 00:32:26.380
which is why the difference between version 2 and version 3

00:32:26.490 --> 00:32:27.240
is going to stay.

00:32:27.600 --> 00:32:28.580
It's not going to change,

00:32:28.960 --> 00:32:31.240
which is why these converters are also immutable,

00:32:31.590 --> 00:32:33.480
which means that you don't need

00:32:33.570 --> 00:32:35.440
to spend much time supporting them.

00:32:37.360 --> 00:32:39.160
Right, once you get, if you're on version three

00:32:39.440 --> 00:32:42.080
and you get the transition from one to two set,

00:32:42.180 --> 00:32:44.280
like that's not gonna change ever, right?

00:32:44.520 --> 00:32:45.980
Exactly, precisely.

